{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502893"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:51:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:51:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1910"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1910"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.25,0.07,0.14,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1910"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90744"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1910"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1910"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74870"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"952"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11122"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31114"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42424"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90744"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents with a six-month history of what he describes as \u0027brittle nails.\u0027 These have become more troublesome and interfere with his job as a plumber. He has a medical history of type 1 diabetes. His medications include insulin. He is an active smoker with a 25 pack-year history. On examination, his fingernails are as shown (Image). The rest of the physical examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment option?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clotrimazole","Fluconazole","Griseofulvin","Ketoconazole","Terbinafine"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a fungal finger nail infection (onychomycosis). Such infections are common, affecting at least 10% of the population and account for some 15% - 40% of all nail diseases.\u00a0\u00a0Up to 50% of dystrophic nails are caused by onychomycosis, and 90% of these cases is due to dermatophyte infection, and the remaining causes are secondary to candida or non-dermatophyte moulds.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for this problem include diabetes, nail injury, immunosuppression, and exposure of fingers to moisture for an extended period of time. The usual infecting agent is \u003Cem\u003ETrichophyton rubrum\u003C/em\u003E. The infection can be confirmed by a simple procedure of clipping the nail or scraping the thickened dystrophic nail to be sent for fungal culture and sensitivity.\u00a0\u00a0There are multiple variations in presentation of onychomycosis, of which distal and lateral subungual onchomycosis is the most common presentation (like the photo shown).\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo appropriate eradicate this infection, the patient will need systemic treatment with oral anti-fungal tablets.\u00a0\u00a0The first line treatment is \u003Cstrong\u003Eterbinafine\u003C/strong\u003E (three month course of fingernails and four months for toenails). Itraconazole is also commonly used, often as a second line agent. However, it is avoided in patients with cardiac conditions (arrhythmia, ventricular dysfunction).\u00a0\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003EFluconazole\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative for those with liver disease and who cannot tolerate terbinafine. \u003Cstrong\u003EGriseofulvin\u003C/strong\u003E has ceased to be the agent of choice as it is associated with a high relapse rate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECandida (which could be treated with \u003Cstrong\u003Eclotrimazole\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eketoconazole\u003C/strong\u003E) is a rare cause of onychomycosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Onychomycosis requires prolonged systemic treatment with an anti-fungal."],"references":["Ameen M, Lear JT, Madan V, et al. British Association of Dermatologists\u2019 guidelines for the management of onychomycosis 2014. Br J Derm 2014;171:937-58. Available at: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/bjd.13358"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74870"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1910"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14976"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14976"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/39298b0b-2ac7-4c91-8508-6b54d171e3c4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/39298b0b-2ac7-4c91-8508-6b54d171e3c4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":431}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74870"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T15:43:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T15:43:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1910"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90744"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"dat